WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.680
 So now I want to show you another example of many-to-many

00:00:02.680 --> 00:00:04.880
 from an application that's near and dear to my heart

00:00:04.880 --> 00:00:06.600
 and that's the autograder that I use

00:00:06.600 --> 00:00:09.200
 for most of my online classes.

00:00:09.200 --> 00:00:11.880
 So one of the things the autograder has to know

00:00:11.880 --> 00:00:14.660
 is like who is in what course

00:00:14.660 --> 00:00:18.320
 so that we can track grades based on people and courses.

00:00:18.320 --> 00:00:20.680
 And so this is the data model

00:00:20.680 --> 00:00:22.720
 and it's a little bit different syntax.

00:00:22.720 --> 00:00:24.200
 You sort of see one-to-many.

00:00:24.200 --> 00:00:26.760
 It's using what's called crow's feet

00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:28.360
 and you see this little crow foot

00:00:28.360 --> 00:00:31.080
 and that's like a many when it sort of spreads out

00:00:31.080 --> 00:00:33.120
 and then you sort of have this one

00:00:33.120 --> 00:00:34.880
 and there's various little ways

00:00:34.880 --> 00:00:37.800
 and one or more or zero or more

00:00:37.800 --> 00:00:40.560
 and so there's little, it's called a crow's foot diagram.

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:43.920
 But these diagrams ultimately are capturing the same thing

00:00:43.920 --> 00:00:45.680
 whether these relationships are many-to-many

00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:47.700
 or one-to-many and what the cardinality

00:00:47.700 --> 00:00:49.540
 of each end of the relationship is.

00:00:49.540 --> 00:00:52.200
 And this is showing a person table,

00:00:52.200 --> 00:00:55.280
 a course table and a membership table

00:00:55.280 --> 00:00:58.240
 and this is a very common thing that we have to solve

00:00:58.240 --> 00:01:01.680
 in educational systems and it's a little bit

00:01:01.680 --> 00:01:04.040
 more sophisticated than the previous one

00:01:04.040 --> 00:01:06.080
 which I thought was beautifully elegant and simple

00:01:06.080 --> 00:01:08.040
 but I wanna show you this one as well.

00:01:08.040 --> 00:01:11.520
 And so what we have here is basically

00:01:11.520 --> 00:01:16.360
 a people are in courses, right?

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:17.880
 A person can be in many courses

00:01:17.880 --> 00:01:19.080
 and a course can have many people

00:01:19.080 --> 00:01:21.080
 so it's a many-to-many relationship.

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:22.120
 We create a through table.

00:01:22.120 --> 00:01:24.040
 We'll call it a member table.

00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:29.040
 We end up just like before with two one-to-many's pointing out

00:01:29.040 --> 00:01:30.860
 or many-to-ones pointing outwards

00:01:30.860 --> 00:01:34.720
 so we have a person ID and a course ID in the member table.

00:01:34.720 --> 00:01:37.280
 All three of these tables have primary keys

00:01:37.280 --> 00:01:41.360
 of ID, ID and ID and then we put the little tiny

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:45.380
 sort of virtual set in here so that at a person

00:01:45.380 --> 00:01:47.960
 you can just look at a virtual set of their courses

00:01:47.960 --> 00:01:51.380
 and of course you can say who are the members of this course.

00:01:52.660 --> 00:01:53.960
 Now we're gonna do one more thing

00:01:53.960 --> 00:01:55.220
 that's a little bit different here

00:01:55.220 --> 00:01:58.940
 and that is often the simplest of through tables

00:01:58.940 --> 00:02:03.060
 is literally an ID and two foreign keys.

00:02:03.060 --> 00:02:04.880
 And as a matter of fact, some people,

00:02:04.880 --> 00:02:06.160
 Django doesn't like doing this

00:02:06.160 --> 00:02:09.120
 but some people don't even include the ID field

00:02:09.120 --> 00:02:10.840
 and they just make the combination

00:02:10.840 --> 00:02:14.560
 of the two foreign keys as a unique ID inside.

00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:16.040
 And if you're doing databases directly

00:02:16.040 --> 00:02:17.420
 you can actually do that.

00:02:17.420 --> 00:02:20.620
 But here's a thing that you can also do.

00:02:20.620 --> 00:02:23.840
 So if you think about in a teaching and learning situation

00:02:23.840 --> 00:02:26.760
 people aren't just members of courses.

00:02:26.760 --> 00:02:28.840
 They are members of courses and they have a role

00:02:28.840 --> 00:02:32.400
 and is that role as a learner, a teaching assistant

00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:34.000
 or an instructor or perhaps

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:36.340
 they're the departmental administrator, right?

00:02:36.340 --> 00:02:41.340
 And that is an attribute of the connection, right?

00:02:41.340 --> 00:02:44.200
 The connection between a person and a course

00:02:44.200 --> 00:02:47.320
 is the membership and oh by the way

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:48.820
 they're not just a member,

00:02:48.820 --> 00:02:52.000
 they're a member with some metadata, okay?

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:54.780
 And so sometimes we add data to the through table

00:02:54.780 --> 00:02:56.480
 and it's actually quite useful

00:02:56.480 --> 00:02:59.440
 and it's really the only place to model this kind of data

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:03.100
 because somebody might be in a course as a teacher

00:03:03.100 --> 00:03:05.380
 and they might be in a different course as a student

00:03:05.380 --> 00:03:07.940
 so you can't just say this person is always a teacher

00:03:07.940 --> 00:03:10.040
 or they're always a student, you can't say that.

00:03:10.040 --> 00:03:12.560
 It depends on the context and so that's why

00:03:12.560 --> 00:03:15.040
 at the connection between a particular person

00:03:15.040 --> 00:03:17.880
 and a particular course we actually model

00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:21.020
 the role that they have in that course.

00:03:21.020 --> 00:03:23.480
 So here we go.

00:03:23.480 --> 00:03:26.880
 So we're going to have a person in a course

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:32.800
 and we're going to have a through table, a membership

00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:34.820
 and so we're gonna send these things

00:03:34.820 --> 00:03:36.960
 back and forth to each other

00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:40.080
 and this membership is the tricky one

00:03:40.080 --> 00:03:42.800
 and so we have a foreign key over to person

00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:44.860
 and a foreign key over to course

00:03:44.860 --> 00:03:46.700
 and we're gonna model some information.

00:03:46.700 --> 00:03:49.160
 We're gonna model a created date at

00:03:49.160 --> 00:03:52.040
 and this is a date time field, this is another feature

00:03:52.040 --> 00:03:55.600
 that basically says let's make a created underscore at

00:03:55.600 --> 00:03:58.700
 and dear Django, I'm not even gonna set this value.

00:03:58.700 --> 00:04:02.400
 Please, when I create this, a new record here,

00:04:02.400 --> 00:04:06.180
 populate this at the current date and time

00:04:06.180 --> 00:04:09.640
 and if I make a change to it, change the updated at

00:04:09.640 --> 00:04:12.440
 and this is a common pattern in lots of tables

00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:17.160
 to put these two lines in and it's so common

00:04:17.160 --> 00:04:19.780
 that we often call them the same field.

00:04:19.780 --> 00:04:21.920
 So you'll look in somebody's Django model

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:24.440
 and you'll see created at and you'll see updated at

00:04:24.440 --> 00:04:26.720
 and so that's another thing we're modeling

00:04:26.720 --> 00:04:31.720
 at the connection in the through table

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:36.800
 and so the other thing we're going to do is have the role.

00:04:36.800 --> 00:04:40.800
 Now the example that you use in local library,

00:04:40.800 --> 00:04:43.480
 they make this role I think a string

00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:47.420
 which makes me kind of like feel bad

00:04:47.420 --> 00:04:49.920
 'cause I don't like vertical replication of string

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:55.520
 even if they're sort of from a fixed vocabulary.

00:04:55.520 --> 00:04:57.360
 So what we're gonna do here is we're gonna do something

00:04:57.360 --> 00:05:01.160
 where we're going to create a set of integers

00:05:01.160 --> 00:05:03.060
 and associate those integers with meaning

00:05:03.060 --> 00:05:05.720
 and use them in the admin interface, et cetera

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:10.200
 and so what I'm gonna do here is these learner IA, GSI,

00:05:10.200 --> 00:05:13.400
 instructor and admin are just integer numbers

00:05:13.400 --> 00:05:15.760
 and then I'm going to say I'm gonna make

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:20.760
 this little tuple of tuples or a list of tuples as it were

00:05:20.760 --> 00:05:25.340
 and the learner integer maps to the string learner

00:05:25.340 --> 00:05:27.440
 so we can show that in the user interface.

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:30.940
 This here is a lot of UI stuff so in the admin UI,

00:05:30.940 --> 00:05:34.900
 this whole member choices thing affects the admin UI.

00:05:34.900 --> 00:05:37.180
 When this is all said and done,

00:05:37.180 --> 00:05:39.840
 we basically say the role is an integer field

00:05:39.840 --> 00:05:43.380
 and I like that because it's short and I love integers.

00:05:43.380 --> 00:05:45.200
 How many times have you heard me say I love integers?

00:05:45.200 --> 00:05:47.520
 Integers are short and efficient

00:05:47.520 --> 00:05:50.160
 and instead of just being any number,

00:05:50.160 --> 00:05:54.840
 it really is the choices are pulled from this thing

00:05:54.840 --> 00:05:56.880
 which is these possible numbers

00:05:56.880 --> 00:06:00.560
 which is one, 1,000, 2,000, 5,000 or 10,000

00:06:00.560 --> 00:06:04.400
 and the default value is learner which means it's a one.

00:06:04.400 --> 00:06:08.180
 So this is a nice, this is basically not,

00:06:08.180 --> 00:06:10.200
 you could make an integer field and we could code

00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:14.260
 in our Python code these numbers and these strings

00:06:14.260 --> 00:06:15.960
 but there's a lot of value in using

00:06:15.960 --> 00:06:17.760
 the administrator interface now

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:21.320
 and having these values known inside the data model

00:06:21.320 --> 00:06:23.180
 rather than just coding them throughout

00:06:23.180 --> 00:06:24.880
 all the Python code that we write.

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:27.360
 So when this is all said and done,

00:06:27.360 --> 00:06:30.120
 what we have is two foreign keys,

00:06:30.120 --> 00:06:32.920
 two outbound foreign keys like you would expect,

00:06:32.920 --> 00:06:35.680
 a created and updated app that's totally maintained

00:06:35.680 --> 00:06:39.320
 by Django for us and then modeled at the connection

00:06:39.320 --> 00:06:42.960
 a role like are you a teacher, are you a student?

00:06:42.960 --> 00:06:46.480
 Okay, and so that's a little more sophisticated

00:06:46.480 --> 00:06:50.400
 kind of many-to-many model and we can talk to this

00:06:50.400 --> 00:06:56.480
 in the Django shell, Python 3, many manage.py shell.

00:06:56.480 --> 00:07:02.820
 You know, we import the models from the application models

00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:05.660
 that this is really reading the models.py file

00:07:05.660 --> 00:07:08.720
 from the many folder, import the person model,

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:12.160
 the course model, membership, those are Python classes.

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:14.740
 We're gonna make a person and save it.

00:07:14.740 --> 00:07:17.020
 We're gonna make a course and save it.

00:07:17.020 --> 00:07:19.540
 We can check the ID to prove that.

00:07:19.540 --> 00:07:22.600
 We can look at all of the members values,

00:07:22.600 --> 00:07:27.600
 that's a query set and then with nothing in it

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:30.460
 and then we can create a membership

00:07:30.460 --> 00:07:32.000
 and we give membership.instructor,

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:33.320
 this is that number, right?

00:07:33.320 --> 00:07:36.920
 I think that was like 1,000 or 5,000 I think what that was

00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:41.080
 and then courses_c, whoops, how come it's not around?

00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:43.040
 There we go, courses_c in person is p,

00:07:43.040 --> 00:07:46.560
 that's taking from the p and c variable that we just created.

00:07:46.560 --> 00:07:49.120
 We are basically populating the true table

00:07:49.120 --> 00:07:52.160
 with the two objects from which we'll figure out

00:07:52.160 --> 00:07:54.800
 what that foreign key is and then we save it.

00:07:54.800 --> 00:07:57.200
 We can see that it's been saved by looking at ID

00:07:59.040 --> 00:08:03.320
 and so we can see these things like c members values now.

00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:05.200
 We can see that this is the person

00:08:05.200 --> 00:08:07.520
 who is a member of that particular course

00:08:07.520 --> 00:08:10.340
 and we can see what courses Ted is in

00:08:10.340 --> 00:08:12.280
 and Ted's in Woodcraft.

00:08:12.280 --> 00:08:16.240
 And so this is just another example using the shell

00:08:16.240 --> 00:08:20.200
 to talk to some many-to-many relations.

00:08:20.200 --> 00:08:21.640
 So up next we're gonna show

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:24.260
 how we do these shell-like operations

00:08:24.260 --> 00:08:26.000
 but we're actually gonna just write Python code

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:27.600
 rather than typing Python code.

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:30.180
 (upbeat music)

